  "text": "The LLVM IR type system flows from type creation through context-owned type pools to machine type lowering in SelectionDAG. Here's the complete chain:\n\n**Type Class Hierarchy and Creation API:**\n\nThe base Type class (llvm/include/llvm/IR/Type.h) defines the type hierarchy with TypeID enums for IntegerTyID, FunctionTyID, StructTyID, etc. Each Type holds a reference to its creating LLVMContext (Type::Context member) and includes ContainedTys and NumContainedTys for composite types.\n\nDerivedTypes.h defines the class hierarchy:\n- IntegerType: Stores bit width in SubclassData, with static factory IntegerType::get(LLVMContext&, unsigned)\n- FunctionType: Stores return type and parameter types in ContainedTys array, with factory FunctionType::get(Type*, ArrayRef<Type*>, bool)\n- StructType: Stores element types in ContainedTys, with factory StructType::get(LLVMContext&, ArrayRef<Type*>, bool)\n\nType.cpp implements these factories with uniquing logic that ensures only one instance exists per unique type signature.\n\n**Context Ownership and Type Pools:**\n\nLLVMContext (llvm/include/llvm/IR/LLVMContext.h) is the public interface that owns all types created within it. The private implementation LLVMContextImpl (llvm/lib/IR/LLVMContextImpl.h, lines 1759-1776) stores type pools:\n\n- DenseMap<unsigned, IntegerType*> IntegerTypes: Maps bit widths to IntegerType instances\n- FoldingSet<FunctionType*> FunctionTypes: Hash set for function type uniquing using FunctionTypeKeyInfo (lines 1761-1762)\n- DenseSet<StructType*> AnonStructTypes: Hash set for anonymous struct uniquing using AnonStructTypeKeyInfo (lines 1763-1764)\n- StringMap<StructType*> NamedStructTypes: Named struct types\n- DenseSet<TargetExtType*> TargetExtTypes: Target extension types using TargetExtTypeKeyInfo\n- DenseMap<std::pair<Type*, uint64_t>, ArrayType*> ArrayTypes\n- DenseMap<std::pair<Type*, ElementCount>, VectorType*> VectorTypes\n- DenseMap<unsigned, PointerType*> PointerTypes\n\nEach Type also has a BumpPtrAllocator (Alloc member at line 1754) for allocation without deallocation.\n\n**IR Type to Machine Type Lowering in SelectionDAG:**\n\nThe type lowering pipeline begins when a SelectionDAG is created with IR types. The DAGTypeLegalizer class (llvm/lib/CodeGen/SelectionDAG/LegalizeTypes.h, line 31) orchestrates transformation from IR types to machine-legal ValueTypes (EVT).\n\nKey components:\n\n1. TargetLowering (llvm/include/llvm/CodeGen/TargetLowering.h) defines which ValueTypes are legal and how operations should be transformed. The TLI field in DAGTypeLegalizer (line 32) provides getTypeAction() to determine how to handle each type: TypeLegal, Promote, Expand, SoftPromoteHalf, etc.\n\n2. DAGTypeLegalizer::run() (LegalizeTypes.cpp, lines 200-251) is the main entry point for type legalization. It walks the SelectionDAG in post-order, visiting leaf nodes first (ReadyToProcess state), then processing nodes as their operands are legalized.\n\n3. Type transformation maps track value transformations:\n   - PromotedIntegers: Small integers promoted to larger types\n   - ExpandedIntegers: Wide integers split into pairs\n   - SoftenedFloats: Floating-point to integer conversion\n   - PromotedFloats: Float precision promotion\n   - ScalarizedVectors: Vectors reduced to scalars\n   - SplitVectors: Wide vectors split\n   - WidenedVectors: Small vectors widened\n\n4. Specialized legalization routines handle each type class:\n   - LegalizeIntegerTypes.cpp: PromoteIntegerResult(), ExpandIntegerResult(), etc.\n   - LegalizeFloatTypes.cpp: SoftenFloatResult(), PromoteFloatResult()\n   - LegalizeVectorTypes.cpp: ScalarizeVectorResult(), SplitVectorResult()\n   - LegalizeTypesGeneric.cpp: Generic expansion and promotion operations\n\nThe chain flows from IR Type→LLVMContext uniquing→SelectionDAG creation with IR types→DAGTypeLegalizer analysis→ValueType legalization→machine-legal code generation. The Type class's immutability and context-based ownership ensures consistent type identity throughout compilation."
}

